---
import Layout from '../../../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Neighbors from "../../../../components/Neighbors.astro";
import PrevNext from "../../../../components/PrevNext.astro";
---

<Layout title="The Construction Gap — Temporal Compression" favicon="🎞️">
  <main>
    <a href="/reading/temporal-compression/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">
      ← back to temporal compression
    </a>

    <h1>The Construction Gap</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">
      Chapter 7 · 22 dead ends and one clean formulation
    </p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">
        The CPS fireworks algorithm produces O(n log n)-sparse temporal spanners.
        The conjecture says O(n) suffice. The log factor lives in one place:
        layered delegation. This chapter maps 22 attempts to kill it and identifies
        the exact combinatorial statement that remains open.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h2>Where the log factor lives</h2>

    <p>
      The fireworks algorithm (<a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1810.00104">Casteigts, Peters &amp; Schoeters 2021</a>)
      works in three phases. First, dismount vertices that can delegate their
      reachability to neighbors — each dismount costs 2 edges. Fully dismountable
      cliques give exactly 2n-3. Second, for the non-dismountable residual (a biclique
      with extremal matchings), run layered delegation: halve the emitters each round,
      paying edges for missed connections.
    </p>

    <p>
      The delegation runs log<sub>2</sub>(k) rounds. Each round costs O(n) edges.
      Log rounds times O(n) per round gives O(n log n). The conjecture says the
      total should be O(n).
    </p>

    <h2>The amortization question</h2>

    <p>
      If the per-round cost scaled with the remaining emitters (not the total),
      the geometric series would converge: k + k/2 + k/4 + ... = 2k = O(n).
      Empirical measurement confirms the per-round cost does scale with remaining
      emitters — but with a log(k) constant baked in.
    </p>

    <p>
      The source: each eliminated emitter generates ~log(k) missed-collector edges
      because the surviving delegate covers only ~1/k of the eliminated emitter's
      collector connections. The sharing is too thin. To get O(n), each elimination
      would need O(1) missed collectors — meaning consecutive emitters in the
      delegation order must share almost all their collector connections.
    </p>

    <h2>The clean formulation</h2>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-6 callout">
      <p style="max-width:none">
        <em>For every non-dismountable biclique with extremal matchings, does there
        exist a delegation order where each eliminated emitter shares all but O(1)
        collectors with its surviving delegate?</em>
      </p>
    </div>

    <p>
      This is a combinatorial statement about matchings. Not about temporal
      reachability, not about the tropical semiring, not about potentials. Just:
      can you order the emitters such that consecutive ones share almost all their
      collector connections? If yes, the 2n-3 conjecture follows from the existing
      CPS machinery with a one-page amortization.
    </p>

    <h2>What doesn't work</h2>

    <p>
      Twenty-two proof techniques were tried against the conjecture. They died for
      four structural reasons:
    </p>

    <h3>Asymmetry kills (6 hypotheses)</h3>
    <p>
      Temporal reachability is forward-transitive but backward-non-transitive.
      Any technique that assumes undirected structure, symmetric composition,
      or time-independent state fails silently. Union-find, Farey trees,
      spanning trees, BGP-style route composition, and symmetric data
      structures all died here.
    </p>

    <h3>Non-locality kills (5 hypotheses)</h3>
    <p>
      An edge's value as a temporal relay depends on global timestamp structure.
      No local heuristic — per-node rules, column degree, timestamp spread,
      Farey mediants — predicts which edges are critical. Local information
      is structurally insufficient.
    </p>

    <h3>Overcorrelation kills (4 hypotheses)</h3>
    <p>
      Relay sets overlap 100%. One edge relays &Theta;(k<sup>2</sup>) pairs —
      a constant fraction of all demand. Double counting, covering arguments,
      and probabilistic methods all die because the relay capacity is too
      concentrated. Random subgraphs with 4k-3 edges are almost never
      spanners — you need ~93% of all edges for random to work.
    </p>

    <h3>Algebraic structure kills (3 hypotheses)</h3>
    <p>
      The tropical semiring lacks additive inverses. Rank-nullity fails.
      No algebraic quantity interpolates between the trivial extremes.
      Spectral methods, lifted-ring factor rank, and LGV determinants
      all compute the right object but can't bound it.
    </p>

    <h2>What does work</h2>

    <p>
      Best-response dynamics (<a href="/data/proof-manual.yml">game equilibrium</a>)
      converge in 2 rounds to a near-optimal spanner (Price of Anarchy &le; 1.25).
      This is the first distributed temporal spanner construction — the literature
      has none. Construction cost is O(k<sup>5</sup>). Not a proof of the conjecture,
      but a publishable algorithm.
    </p>

    <p>
      The fireworks algorithm itself always produces &le; 2n-3 edges empirically,
      verified through n=10. The analysis is what's loose — the algorithm is fine.
    </p>

    <h2>The negative mold</h2>

    <p>
      After 22 dead ends, we know what the proof must look like:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>Combinatorial (algebraic structure is too weak)</li>
      <li>Constructive (probabilistic methods can't find structured spanners)</li>
      <li>Global (local heuristics have zero predictive power)</li>
      <li>Asymmetric (must respect forward-but-not-backward transitivity)</li>
      <li>Specific to dismountability structure (bespoke, not off-the-shelf)</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      The proof manual (<a href="https://github.com/kimjune01/june.kim/blob/master/src/data/proof-manual.yml">proof-manual.yml</a>)
      was applied systematically. Every candidate from the claim &times; domain grid
      was checked against kill conditions. The manual correctly surfaces candidates
      but cannot generate the bespoke construction — that's the frontier.
    </p>

    <h2>For the next attempt</h2>

    <p>
      The tightest path to 2n-3 is not a new proof technique. It's a tighter
      analysis of the existing fireworks algorithm. The delegation cost is
      O(log k) missed collectors per eliminated emitter. Reducing this to O(1)
      requires an ordering of emitters where consecutive ones share collectors.
      This is a question about matchings in bipartite graphs — a classical
      combinatorial object with deep theory.
    </p>

    <p>
      The matching-sharing question may itself be open. If so, the conjecture
      reduces to it cleanly. If it's false (some bicliques don't admit
      sharing-rich orderings), then O(n log n) is tight and the conjecture
      needs a fundamentally different construction.
    </p>

    <PrevNext
      prev={{ href: "/reading/temporal-compression/ch-06/", title: "← The Rosetta Stone" }}
    />
  </main>
</Layout>
